<font color="#FF0000">WAR AGAINST CIVILIANS!</font><br>
<tt>Thu Feb 13  5:40:22 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Irregardless of the political ramifications of using such a device as a neutron bomb, there are the moral and ethical considerations.  By definition, the neutron bomb produces minimal heat and blast effects, but douses the intended area with massive quanities of highly lethal neutron and gamma radiation.  The &quot;enemy&quot; would not die immediately, but would die a slow and agonizing death that would linger upwards to six days or so.  Except for those at ground zero, nobody would be killed outright.<br><br>
Initially, the purpose of such a device was for defense against infantry and armoured assualts.  The rational was that the devices could be used as a tactical weapon for ground forces without affecting surrounding cities.  There is not a tank or armour vehicle that can stop this source of radiation. Over the years, this had changed to which entire cities could be &quot;depopulated&quot; without the destruction of the cities themselves.  Thus, saving the property of the cities for the victors.<br><br>
This is the answer of which Angela proposes.<br><br>
Lets do some math.  An average city of, lets say, 100,000 people.  Out of this, approximately 30,000 are men, not military, but civilian.  Another 35,000 are women, again, not military, but civilian.  That leaves 35,000 of which are kids ranging from newborns to sixteen years of age.<br><br>
We take this city and saturate it with nuetron devices.  By any miracle, if any are uneffected by the radiation, would there be enough to care for the 99% of the population who are lying in the streets, puking and shitting blood, writhering in convulsions, unable to eat or drink, or if &quot;God&quot; is merciful, lying in their own stench in a coma?<br><br>
Lets take Vietnam.  It is evident that these devices would have had very little effect on the NVA or the Viet Cong forces unless the were caught in huge numbers AND above ground.  However, that was not the typical type of fighting done by these forces.<br><br>
Could we have used these devices on Hanoi and other large populated areas?  Hanoi, yes. Other large cities, no.  North Vietnam did not have them.  The concentration of large cities were in the south.  By depopulating Hanoi, would it have changed anything?  The entire military and political structure of North Vietnam would have been uneffected.  In the case of Vietnam,the only use for this type of weapon is to wage war against civilians.<br><br>
Can any see any practical use of such a weapon?<br><br>
Oh yes, about praying to God.  Didn't help then, why would it help now?
